n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maximumLength(self, nums: List[int], k: int) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def maximumLength(self, nums: List[int], k: int) -> int:\n        n = len(nums)\n        f = [[1] * (k + 1) for _ in range(n)]\n        ans = 0\n        for i, x in enumerate(nums):\n            for h in range(k + 1):\n                for j, y in enumerate(nums[:i]):\n                    if x == y:\n                        f[i][h] = max(f[i][h], f[j][h] + 1)\n                    elif h:\n                        f[i][h] = max(f[i][h], f[j][h - 1] + 1)\n            ans = max(ans, f[i][k])\n        return ans\n```\n\nThis solution uses dynamic programming to solve the problem. The `f[i][h]` array keeps track of the maximum length of a good subsequence that ends at index `i` with at most `h` changes. The solution iterates through each element in the array and updates the `f` array based on the conditions provided in the problem statement. Finally, it returns the maximum value found in `f[i][k]` for all `i`, which represents the maximum length of a good subsequence with at most `k` changes.", "estimated_date": 1717286400000}